00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:17.460
Why does Llama CPP use so much less RAM for the same model?

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:21.760
I think it's mainly, I mean, it's written just to do this one thing, right?

00:16:21.760 --> 00:16:24.760
So obviously to do with sentence transformers needs Python,

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:26.760
Python can do a lot more than one thing.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:30.760
And then Python needs, the dependencies that sentence transformer needs

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:33.760
are things like PyTorch and all these kind of big general purpose

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:38.760
tensor math things that, and so I think Llama CPP can strip away all of that

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:41.760
and it's written in C++ directly as opposed to being written in Python.

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:43.760
So I think that's the answer.

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:47.559
For the emoji search,

00:16:47.559 --> 00:16:51.559
was there more difficulty with emojis that were face-like versus items?

00:16:51.559 --> 00:16:55.559
Well, I encode the description of the text.

00:16:55.559 --> 00:16:58.559
So there's a Python package called emoji, pip install emoji,

00:16:58.559 --> 00:17:01.559
and inside of there, there is basically an emoji data dictionary

00:17:01.559 --> 00:17:04.560
and I turned that into a pandas data frame and that's how I got.

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:07.560
So I'm not actually encoding the emoji, I'm encoding, like, the string.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.560
So yeah, some of them are weird, some of them are very specific,

00:17:10.560 --> 00:17:12.560
like smiling, you know, eyes.

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:16.359
The description of these emojis, sometimes they're more helpful than others.

00:17:16.359 --> 00:17:20.359
So the ones that have kind of long and not particularly helpful descriptions

00:17:20.359 --> 00:17:23.359
that are very specific, it's hard to find them semantically.

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:26.359
Obviously, some emojis you're better off searching not semantically

00:17:26.359 --> 00:17:29.359
but searching for just in another way.

00:17:29.359 --> 00:17:32.359
And so yeah, some of them, you know,

00:17:32.359 --> 00:17:35.359
the model's going to do what it's going to do

00:17:35.359 --> 00:17:38.359
and some things it returns easily and some things it doesn't.

00:17:38.359 --> 00:17:41.359
Like turtle and slow, I can't get that to work.

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:45.160
Semantic search seems to be more prevalent than ever

00:17:45.160 --> 00:17:48.160
with the rise of LLMs and RAG.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:51.160
Is cosine similarity still the best way to do this?

00:17:51.160 --> 00:17:54.160
Have there been any interesting innovations?

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:57.160
That is a very good question.

00:17:57.160 --> 00:18:00.160
I think it really depends on how, and I am not an expert on language models,

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:03.160
I think it really depends on how they build the model.

00:18:03.160 --> 00:18:06.160
I think some of these models are built to kind of, are kind of constructed

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:09.160
in a way that cosine similarity is like the best tool to use

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:12.160
to actually optimize for dot product.

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:15.160
So it really depends on how they built the model.

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:18.160
I think cosine similarity is still reasonable for most of them

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:21.160
but it does depend on how they construct the model

00:18:21.160 --> 00:18:24.160
and the vectors that come out of it.

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:27.160
